cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.DS, cs.SI, cs.CC

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper proposes an improved degree distribution for Luby Transform (LT) codes and evaluates its performance in terms of bit error rate. This falls under the domain of information theory.
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper applies the proposed degree distribution to distributed multi-source relay networks, which is a networking concept.
3. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper uses And-Or tree analysis to evaluate the performance of the proposed LT codes, which is a data structure used in algorithm design.
4. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper proposes a transmission scheme based on the proposed degree distribution to improve frame error rate, which can be applied to social and information networks.
5. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper mentions reduced complexity in low overhead regions, which is a concept related to computational complexity.
